LEPTOSPIROSIS - USA (03): (NEW YORK) ex ISRAEL, TEENAGE TRAVELERS
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 11 Oct 2018
Source: Journal of Travel Medicine [edited]
https://doi.org/10.1093/jtm/tay101 [subscription required]


ref: Birabaharan M, Hagmann SHF. Importation of leptospirosis to New York from Israel by teen travelers. J Travel Med. 2018. doi: 10.1093/jtm/tay101
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The current leptospirosis outbreak in Northern Israel with 36 confirmed/probably and 583 suspected cases, has been a concerning health risk among all travelers visiting this region, but special surveillance seemed warranted for adolescents.(1) Israel is a popular summer destination among youths for camps, tours, and fresh-water recreational activities; making up to 40% of all visitors.(2) Therefore, physicians should have raised clinical awareness for young travelers returning from Israel with an acute febrile illness. We report three cases of suspected leptospirosis, one confirmed, of teenaged travelers to Israel.

All 3 patients had spent about 4 weeks in Israel in July/August [2018] and had visited affected bodies of water in the Golan Heights with various fresh water exposure (kayaking, swimming, or white-water-rafting). The 1st patient was a 16-year-old male who returned to the US in the 1st week of August [2018] and one week later developed general lethargy, fever, headache, and myalgia. He subsequently presented with signs of meningitis. The diagnosis of leptospirosis was made with a commercially available IgM ELISA-assay with a positive convalescent sample one month later. The 2nd patient was a 16 year-old female who had started to experience intermittent fevers, headaches, neck pain and myalgia while still in Israel. Upon her return her headaches worsened and were associated with blurry vision. A diagnosis of aseptic meningitis secondary due to probable leptospirosis was made. However, diagnostic screening tests with the IgM ELISA-assay during the acute illness, and at subsequent follow-up one week later were negative. Lastly, a 16-year-old male presented with fever and headache 10 days after return. A teen co-traveler had been diagnosed and treated for leptospirosis. His diagnostic screening test (IgM ELISA-assay) for leptospirosis obtained during the acute presentation was negative. Leptospirosis-specific PCR from blood had been sent only for the first patient and was negative, and none of the three patients were available for additional testing with the microscopic agglutination (MAT) test. All received treatment with ceftriaxone, doxycycline or azithromycin for 5-7 days and had made full recovery.

Clinical manifestations of leptospirosis range from mild to severe. Most present with nonspecific symptoms of fever, headache, myalgia, abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Aseptic meningitis as seen in 2 of our patients occurs frequently. The more severe icteric presentations (Weil syndrome) affect only about 10% of patients with leptospirosis. Laboratory diagnosis of leptospirosis remains a challenge. PCR-assays represent the test of choice during the acute illness but may not be readily available while ELISA for the detection of leptospira-specific IgM antibodies is most frequently used but is limited by variable sensitivities.(3,4) In the US a confirmatory MAT assay [microscopic agglutination test] is available through the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

In summary, we would like to emphasize that due to the potential of a severe disease course alongside imperfect laboratory diagnostic tools, a high clinical suspicion of leptospirosis may be warranted when evaluating teen travelers with an acute febrile illness as they are likely to engage in fresh water activities even when returning from a destination not usually considered endemic for leptospirosis.(5)

