[Leptospirosis is a notifiable disease in Israel for both humans and animals. When the disease is reported in animals, the relevant State Veterinary Officer is obliged by law to report the event at the earliest to the Public Health authorities, enabling timely preventive measures undertaken. Surveillance in animals is required to warrant effective protection of public health.

Leptospirosis used to be included in OIE's list for decades, prescribing requirements for international trade to prevent the transboundary spread of strains that are considered exotic in importing countries. However, during the 79th General Session of the OIE, Paris, May 2011, Leptospirosis was removed from the OIE list of diseases. The following text on the meeting's discussions was included on page 221 of the conference's report (http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/About_us/docs/pdf/A_FR_2011_PUB.pdf):

"Removal of leptospirosis from the OIE list of diseases:
Dr Barcos stated that the OIE Code was not only used for the purposes of international trade, but was highly useful in developing national legislation and setting up programmes and activities. He added that the countries of the Americas had called for leptospirosis not to be excluded from the OIE list, as this would leave Members without a legal basis and technical reference.

Dr Alex Thiermann, President of the Code Commission, replied that, given the endemic nature of this disease worldwide, it was inappropriate to keep it in the Code. However, he said that the chapter on leptospirosis in the Manual would remain."

The Manual's chapter 2.1.12 Leptospirosis, adopted by World Assembly of Delegates of the OIE in May 2014, is available at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.01.12_LEPTO.pdf.

In late 2016, a dairy operation in northern Israel was found severely affected by _Leptospira interrogans_ serovar Pomona, hitherto uncommon in Israel. It was suspected that the bacterium may had been introduced by calves imported for local fattening, kept on the same premises; see commentary with additional details and (pending) questions in ProMED-mail post archive number 20170202.4811833.

The identity of the leptospira strain(s) which is/are behind the recent event on the Golan Heights, involving hundreds of human patients, circulating in cattle and, most probably, wild boars, involving visitors from Germany and USA, is yet to be finalised and published. Similarly, results of the surveillance in animals is yet to be finalised and results published.

The Ministry of Health's ban on entrance/swimming in 6 bodies of water on the Golan Heights has not yet been withdrawn. - Mod.AS

